<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCD481AFC99F8AEFBDAAC96" authorityName="Agudelo &amp; Maldaner &amp; Rafael" authorityYear="2019" box="[846,1070,1902,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metacanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="2" pageNumber="333" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscum">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCD481AFC99F8AEFBDAAC96" box="[846,1070,1902,1924]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="333">Metacanthops fuscum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCD481AFBE9F8AEFB8EAC96" bold="true" box="[1086,1146,1902,1924]" pageId="2" pageNumber="333">n. sp.</emphasis>
), a male with fully dry-leaf habitus (specimen from Reserva Cuieiras, ZF2, Manaus, Amazonas State, Brazil—Photo by Antonio Agudelo); 4, 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCD481AFF40F86CFEC9ACD0" authorityName="Saussure" authorityYear="1871" box="[151,317,1964,1986]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Pseudacanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="2" pageNumber="333" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCD481AFF40F86CFEC9ACD0" box="[151,317,1964,1986]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="333">Pseudacanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., a female resembling a lichenous twig (specimen from Manaus, Amazonas State, Brazil—Photo by Antonio Agudelo).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C33F6522FFCC481BFF10FF57FEC8AF45" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9A36A9FFCC481BFF10FF57FB35A972" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF10FF57FECFABA2" bold="true" box="[199,315,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Remarks.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFE91FF57FE11ABA2" box="[326,485,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFD51FF57FD23ABA2" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[646,727,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFD51FF57FD23ABA2" box="[646,727,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having uniformly brown forewings, whereas the same in 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFF40FF7CFF1CABC7" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[151,232,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF40FF7CFF1CABC7" box="[151,232,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vary from dark green to yellow. However, it is in the head where conspicuous differences between 
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF40FF1FFEC2ABEA" box="[151,310,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFEA4FF1FFE30ABEA" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[371,452,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFEA4FF1FFE30ABEA" box="[371,452,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and between them and 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFD30FF1FFCA9ABEA" authorityName="Serville" authorityYear="1831" box="[743,861,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFD30FF1FFCA9ABEA" box="[743,861,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be observed (
<figureCitation id="131E2A2CFFCC481BFBE0FF1FFB30ABEA" box="[1079,1220,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–22" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1547,1569]" captionTargetBox="[355,1237,414,1520]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[350,1237,409,1526]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 13–22. Summary of key morphological features to distinguish Acanthops and Metilia from Metacanthops: 13, head of Acanthops erosula, female (laterofrontal view); 14, head of Metilia sp., female (laterofrontal view); 15, Head of Metacanthops fuscum n. sp., female (laterofrontal view); 16, head of Metilia sp., male (frontal view); 17, head of Metacanthops fuscum, male (frontal view); 18, pronotum of Metacanthops fuscum, female (dorsal view),19: pronotum of Metilia sp., female (dorsal view); 20, male phallic complex of Metilia sp.; 21: male phallic complex of Metacanthops fuscum n. sp; 22: male phallic complex of Metacanthops amazonica n. comb. Abbreviations: right epiphallus (rph); basisclerite (bscl); left epiphallus (lph); titillator (ti); pseudophallus (psph); hypophallus (hph); apophysis (apo). Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627715/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Figs. 13–22</figureCitation>
). For instance, the compound eyes of 
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFEBEFEC4FDF3AA0F" box="[361,519,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
are only slightly conical and bear a small apical wart, whereas the same in 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFA9CFEC4FA68AA0F" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[1355,1436,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFA9CFEC4FA68AA0F" box="[1355,1436,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFF11FEE7FEC8AA52" authorityName="Serville" authorityYear="1831" box="[198,316,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF11FEE7FEC8AA52" box="[198,316,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are strongly conical with a more developed apical wart; the vertex of 
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFB98FEE7FB1AAA52" box="[1103,1262,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
rises above the compound eyes, in the males it has distinct undulations in its central area and conspicuous juxtaocular process in females (
<figureCitation id="131E2A2CFFCC481BFF2AFEAFFE70AA9A" box="[253,388,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–22" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1547,1569]" captionTargetBox="[355,1237,414,1520]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[350,1237,409,1526]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 13–22. Summary of key morphological features to distinguish Acanthops and Metilia from Metacanthops: 13, head of Acanthops erosula, female (laterofrontal view); 14, head of Metilia sp., female (laterofrontal view); 15, Head of Metacanthops fuscum n. sp., female (laterofrontal view); 16, head of Metilia sp., male (frontal view); 17, head of Metacanthops fuscum, male (frontal view); 18, pronotum of Metacanthops fuscum, female (dorsal view),19: pronotum of Metilia sp., female (dorsal view); 20, male phallic complex of Metilia sp.; 21: male phallic complex of Metacanthops fuscum n. sp; 22: male phallic complex of Metacanthops amazonica n. comb. Abbreviations: right epiphallus (rph); basisclerite (bscl); left epiphallus (lph); titillator (ti); pseudophallus (psph); hypophallus (hph); apophysis (apo). Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627715/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Figs. 14–17</figureCitation>
), whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFDC1FEAFFD93AA9A" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[534,615,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFDC1FEAFFD93AA9A" box="[534,615,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFD4BFEAFFCE6AA9A" authorityName="Serville" authorityYear="1831" box="[668,786,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFD4BFEAFFCE6AA9A" box="[668,786,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these features are missing. 
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFB93FEAFFB17AA9A" box="[1092,1251,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
has a robust and tuberculated pronotum, but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFE24FE54FDB0AABF" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[499,580,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFE24FE54FDB0AABF" box="[499,580,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the same is relatively narrower and smooth (
<figureCitation id="131E2A2CFFCC481BFB99FE54FB2FAABE" box="[1102,1243,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–22" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1547,1569]" captionTargetBox="[355,1237,414,1520]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[350,1237,409,1526]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 13–22. Summary of key morphological features to distinguish Acanthops and Metilia from Metacanthops: 13, head of Acanthops erosula, female (laterofrontal view); 14, head of Metilia sp., female (laterofrontal view); 15, Head of Metacanthops fuscum n. sp., female (laterofrontal view); 16, head of Metilia sp., male (frontal view); 17, head of Metacanthops fuscum, male (frontal view); 18, pronotum of Metacanthops fuscum, female (dorsal view),19: pronotum of Metilia sp., female (dorsal view); 20, male phallic complex of Metilia sp.; 21: male phallic complex of Metacanthops fuscum n. sp; 22: male phallic complex of Metacanthops amazonica n. comb. Abbreviations: right epiphallus (rph); basisclerite (bscl); left epiphallus (lph); titillator (ti); pseudophallus (psph); hypophallus (hph); apophysis (apo). Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627715/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Figs. 18, 19</figureCitation>
). The number of forefemoral posteroventral spines apparently constitutes a good diagnostic character in this case, as we consistently found 6 spines in all studied specimens of 
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFDBAFE1CFCF8AAE7" box="[621,780,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
(however, in few rare cases some specimens have 5 or 
<quantity id="4CDD9B4CFFCC481BFAA5FE1DFA68AAE7" box="[1394,1436,476,501]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
only one of their prothoracic legs), whereas we consistently found 7 forefemoral posteroventral spines across all specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFEE4FDE4FE70A92F" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[307,388,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFEE4FDE4FE70A92F" box="[307,388,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(unpublished data). In addition, the margins of tergites V and VI are slightly prominent and rectangular in 
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFEEFFD87FE22A972" box="[312,470,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFDB3FD87FD41A972" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[612,693,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFDB3FD87FD41A972" box="[612,693,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are dilated, semicircular or subtriangular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9A36A9FFCC481BFF10FDACFEC8AF45" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">
The reliability of certain characters to separate acanthopid genera, such as vertex features, wing shape, abdominal appendages and, particularly, the number of forefemoral spines, have been a matter of controversy (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFF49FD74FEBEA9DF" author="Chopard, L." box="[158,330,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="161 - 187" refId="ref8140" refString="Chopard, L. (1916) Etudes des mantides americains de la Colection I Bolivar. Annales de la Societe entomologique de France, 85, 161 - 187." type="journal article" year="1916">Chopard 1916</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFE8AFD74FDD4A9DE" author="Giglio-Tos, E." box="[349,544,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="1 - 707" refId="ref8266" refString="Giglio-Tos, E. (1927) Orthoptera, Mantidae. Das Tierreich. 50, 1 - 707." type="journal article" year="1927">Giglio-Tos 1927</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFDE5FD74FD42A9DF" author="Rehn, J. A. G." box="[562,694,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="162 - 272" refId="ref8805" refString="Rehn, J. A. G. (1935) The Orthoptera of Costa Rica. I. Mantodea. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 87, 162 - 272." type="journal article" year="1935">Rehn 1935</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFD1EFD75FCB9A9DF" author="Terra, P." box="[713,845,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="13 - 94" refId="ref9348" refString="Terra, P. (1995) Revisao sistematica dos Generos de Louva-a-Deus da regiao Neotropical (Mantodea). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 39 (1), 13 - 94." type="journal article" year="1995">Terra 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFC88FD75FC2DA9DE" author="Roy, R." box="[863,985,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="171 - 177" refId="ref9026" refString="Roy, R. (2002) Commentaires a`propos du genre Plesiacanthops Chopard, 1913 et redescription de Acanthops tuberculata Saussure, 1870. (Dictyoptera, Mantodea). Revue francaise d'Entomologie, 24, 171 - 177." type="journal article" year="2002">Roy 2002</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFC24FD74FB58A9DF" author="Chopard, L." box="[1011,1196,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="161 - 187" refId="ref8140" refString="Chopard, L. (1916) Etudes des mantides americains de la Colection I Bolivar. Annales de la Societe entomologique de France, 85, 161 - 187." type="journal article" year="1916">Chopard (1916)</bibRefCitation>
considered that the diagnostic characters of 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFE15FD17FD99A9E2" authorityName="Chopard" authorityYear="1913" box="[450,621,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Plesiacanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFE15FD17FD99A9E2" box="[450,621,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Plesiacanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFD53FD17FD21A9E2" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[644,725,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFD53FD17FD21A9E2" box="[644,725,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFD3BFD19FC93A9E2" authorityName="Uvarov" authorityYear="1940" box="[748,871,729,752]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Decimiana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFD3BFD19FC93A9E2" box="[748,871,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Decimiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, were all of little relevance for making such distinction, and thus he considered these genera merely as &quot;subdivisions&quot; of 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFBF5FD3CFB6CA807" authorityName="Serville" authorityYear="1831" box="[1058,1176,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFBF5FD3CFB6CA807" box="[1058,1176,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFAF4FD3CFF15A82A" author="Giglio-Tos, E." pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="1 - 707" refId="ref8266" refString="Giglio-Tos, E. (1927) Orthoptera, Mantidae. Das Tierreich. 50, 1 - 707." type="journal article" year="1927">Giglio-Tos (1927)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFECAFCDFFE58A82A" author="Rehn, J. A. G." box="[285,428,799,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="162 - 272" refId="ref8805" refString="Rehn, J. A. G. (1935) The Orthoptera of Costa Rica. I. Mantodea. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 87, 162 - 272." type="journal article" year="1935">Rehn (1935)</bibRefCitation>
considered that those characters were valid because they are commonly used at genuslevel in other mantodean taxa. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFDDDFC85FD64A84E" author="Roy, R." box="[522,656,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="171 - 177" refId="ref9026" refString="Roy, R. (2002) Commentaires a`propos du genre Plesiacanthops Chopard, 1913 et redescription de Acanthops tuberculata Saussure, 1870. (Dictyoptera, Mantodea). Revue francaise d'Entomologie, 24, 171 - 177." type="journal article" year="2002">Roy (2002)</bibRefCitation>
recently revisited this issue and suggested that the differentiation between 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFF2BFCA7FEB9A892" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[252,333,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF2BFCA7FEB9A892" box="[252,333,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFE53FCA7FE0EA892" authorityName="Serville" authorityYear="1831" box="[388,506,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFE53FCA7FE0EA892" box="[388,506,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be justified based on the number of forefemoral posteroventral spines. For instance, he argued that 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFE7DFC4CFD5CA8B7" box="[426,680,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFE7DFC4CFD5CA8B7" box="[426,680,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 7 posteroventral spines, unlike the rest of species in the genus with only 6 spines, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFE03FC70FD98A8DA" authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1930" box="[468,620,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFE03FC70FD98A8DA" box="[468,620,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">A. amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(which normally presents 6, but males sometimes having 5 or 
<quantity id="4CDD9B4CFFCC481BFAFCFC70FAA2A8DA" box="[1323,1366,943,968]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
either forefemur) should be transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFDFFFC14FD8DA8FF" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[552,633,980,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFDFFFC14FD8DA8FF" box="[552,633,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whose species also have 7 spines. Although we agree with 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFACBFC15FA68A8FE" author="Roy, R." box="[1308,1436,980,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="171 - 177" refId="ref9026" refString="Roy, R. (2002) Commentaires a`propos du genre Plesiacanthops Chopard, 1913 et redescription de Acanthops tuberculata Saussure, 1870. (Dictyoptera, Mantodea). Revue francaise d'Entomologie, 24, 171 - 177." type="journal article" year="2002">Roy (2002)</bibRefCitation>
in that 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFF3FFC39FE96AF02" authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1930" box="[232,354,1017,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF3FFC39FE96AF02" box="[232,354,1017,1040]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not a member of 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFD9CFC37FD35AF02" authorityName="Serville" authorityYear="1831" box="[587,705,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFD9CFC37FD35AF02" box="[587,705,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the newly available evidence suggest that its placement among 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFF40FBDCFF1CAF27" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1877" box="[151,232,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Metilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF40FBDCFF1CAF27" box="[151,232,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be reconsidered. Accordingly, we now formally transfer 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D2AFFCC481BFC3DFBDCFA8EAF26" authority="Beier, 1930" authorityName="Beier" authorityYear="1930" box="[1002,1402,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthopidae" genus="Acanthops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mantodea" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFC3DFBDCFB12AF26" box="[1002,1254,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Acanthops amazonica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB44B58FFCC481BFB24FBDCFA8EAF26" author="Beier, M." box="[1267,1402,1052,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="334" pagination="27 - 32" refId="ref7857" refString="Beier, M. (1930) Ergebnisse einer zoologischen Sammelreise nach Brasilien, insbesondere in das Amazonasgebiet, ausgefuhrt von Dr. H. Zerny. Annalen Naturhistorisches Museum Wien, 44, 27 - 32." type="journal article" year="1930">Beier, 1930</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<emphasis id="B951EABBFFCC481BFF40FBFFFEC1AF4A" box="[151,309,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="334">Metacanthops</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
